\]

Method 1: Consider two events: Event \( A \), when the person departs; Event \( B \), when the person reaches the distant galaxy. The Earth and the distant galaxy are in frame \( S \), and the spaceship is in frame \( S^{\prime} \),

\[
x_{B} - x_{A} = \frac{x_{B}^{\prime} - x_{A}^{\prime} + v\left(t_{B}^{\prime} - t_{A}^{\prime}\right)}{\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{v}{c}\right)^2}} \tag{1}
\]

Here, \( x_{B}^{\prime} - x_{A}^{\prime} = 0 \), and \( t_{B}^{\prime} - t_{A}^{\prime} = 60 \) years (considering he should just be able to reach the distant galaxy within his lifetime).

\[
\begin{gathered}
(\Delta x)^2 \left(1-\frac{v^2}{c^2}\right) = v^2 (\Delta t^{\prime})^2 \\
v = \frac{\Delta x}{\sqrt{\left(\frac{\Delta x}{c}\right)^2 + (\Delta t^{\prime})^2}}
\end{gathered}
\]

Substitute \(\Delta x = 160000c\) (time in years)

\[
\begin{aligned}
v & = \frac{160000c}{\sqrt{(160000)^2 + (60)^2}} = \frac{c}{\sqrt{1 + \left( \frac{60}{160000} \right)^2}} \\
  & = c \left[ 1 - \frac{1}{2} \left( \frac{60}{160000} \right)^2 \right] = \left( 1 - 7.03 \times 10^{-8} \right)c
\end{aligned}
\]

由 $\frac{\partial x^{\prime \mu}}{\partial x^{\alpha}} = \delta_{\alpha}^{\mu} + \varepsilon_{\ , \alpha}^{\mu}$，所以

$$
\begin{aligned}
g_{\mu \nu}^{\prime}\left(x^{\prime}\right) & = \frac{\partial x^{\prime \alpha}}{\partial x^{\mu}} \frac{\partial x^{\prime \beta}}{\partial x^{\nu}} g_{\alpha \beta}(x) = \left(\delta_{\mu}^{\alpha} + \varepsilon_{,\mu}^{\alpha}\right)\left(\delta_{\nu}^{\beta} + \varepsilon_{,\nu}^{\beta}\right) g_{\alpha \beta}(x) \\
& \approx g_{\mu \nu}(x) + g_{\alpha \nu}(x) \varepsilon_{,\mu}^{\alpha} + g_{\mu \beta}(x) \varepsilon_{,\nu}^{\beta}
\end{aligned}
$$

利用泰勒展开式可得

$$
g_{\mu \nu}^{\prime}\left(x^{\prime}\right) = g_{\mu \nu}(x) + g_{\mu \nu,\alpha}(x) \varepsilon^{\alpha}
$$

故

$$
g_{\mu \nu}^{\prime}(x) = g_{\mu \nu}(x) - g_{\mu \nu,\alpha}(x) \varepsilon^{\alpha} + g_{\alpha \nu}(x) \varepsilon_{,\mu}^{\alpha} + g_{\mu \beta}(x) \varepsilon_{,\nu}^{\beta}
$$

但 $g_{\mu \nu}^{\prime} = \eta_{\mu \nu} + h_{\mu \nu}^{\prime}$，所以 $h_{\mu \nu}^{\prime} = h_{\mu \nu} + \varepsilon_{\mu,\nu} + \varepsilon_{\nu,\mu}$。
由场方程

$$
\square h_{\mu \nu} = \theta_{\mu,\nu} + \theta_{\nu,\mu}
$$

所以

$$
\begin{aligned}
\square h_{\mu \nu}^{\prime} & = \theta_{\mu,\nu} + \theta_{\nu,\mu} + \square \varepsilon_{\mu,\nu} + \square \varepsilon_{\nu,\mu} \\
& = \theta_{\mu,\nu}^{\prime} + \theta_{\nu,\mu}^{\prime} - \varepsilon_{,\alpha \alpha \nu} - \square \varepsilon_{\mu,\nu} + \frac{1}{2} \varepsilon_{,\alpha,\nu} + \frac{1}{2} \varepsilon_{,\alpha \alpha \nu}
\end{aligned}
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& - \varepsilon_{,\nu \alpha \alpha} - \square \varepsilon_{\nu,\mu} + \frac{1}{2} \varepsilon_{,\alpha,\mu} + \frac{1}{2} \varepsilon_{,\alpha \alpha \mu} + \square \varepsilon_{\mu,\nu} + \square \varepsilon_{\nu,\mu} \\
= & \theta_{\mu,\nu}^{\prime} + \theta_{\nu,\mu}^{\prime}
\end{aligned}
$$

因此满足规范不变性。

problem:
A photon with energy \( E_{
u} \) collides with an electron having energy \( E \gg m_{0} c^{2} \) (\( m_{0} \) is the rest mass). In the laboratory reference frame, the angle between the directions of the photon's movement and the electron's movement is \( 	heta \). Before the collision, the energy of the photon in the electron's reference frame is \( E_{
u}^{\prime} \), and \( E_{
u}^{\prime} \ll m_{0} c^{2} \), meaning the recoil of the electron can be ignored. The photon's energy in the electron's reference frame does not change due to the collision. What are the minimum and maximum values of the photon's energy in the laboratory reference frame after the collision?

solution:
The derived expressions for the energy and momentum of a relativistic particle are:

$$
\begin{gathered}
E = mc^2 = \frac{m_0 c^2}{\sqrt{1 - \frac{v^2}{c^2}}} \\
p_x = \frac{m_0}{\sqrt{1 - \frac{v^2}{c^2}}} \dot{x}, \quad p_y = \frac{m_0}{\sqrt{1 - \frac{v^2}{c^2}}} \dot{y}, \quad p_z = \frac{m_0}{\sqrt{1 - \frac{v^2}{c^2}}} \dot{z} \\
p^2 = p_x^2 + p_y^2 + p_z^2 = \frac{m_0^2 (\dot{x}^2 + \dot{y}^2 + \dot{z}^2)}{1 - \frac{v^2}{c^2}} = \frac{m_0^2 v^2}{1 - \frac{v^2}{c^2}} \\
v^2 = \frac{c^2 p^2}{m_0^2 c^2 + p^2}
\end{gathered}
$$
